CSV Puzzle Solution - Nathaniel Smith¶

Welcome! Browsing the web a download link to a basic two-column .csv "puzzle" which I believed I solved below. This file is the documentation on how I did it, with respective credit to the developers of the libraries utlized. A python file is included in the git repo to reproduce my work avalible here.¶

As soon as I saw the file was two columns of numbers, my mind immediately went to coordinates. After simply graphing the points and modifying their orientation, it became clear it was a map of some sorts.¶

Access the coordinates puzzle and import into pandas dataframe:¶
In [1]:

It became clear I would need to plot the points with a more detailed map.¶

After exploring multiple libraries to map coordinates, I chose folium, a lightweight library to make simple interactive HTML maps. Before deciding on this, I experimented with basemap and matplotlib.¶

Import the appropriate python libraries:¶
In [3]:
import folium
import math
import pandas as pd
from IPython.display import HTML

To display the maps in this document, I created the following function:¶

In [4]:
def show(folmap):
    """Displays in the notebook a folium.folium.Map object.
    """
    folmap.render()
    iframe = folmap._repr_html_()
    return HTML(iframe)

To plot the coordinates from the original file onto a folium object, I created the following function:¶

In [5]:
def plotPoints(df, map):
    for i in range(len(df)):
        """ plots all points in a dataframe in folium, which generates an HTML file with all \
        points plotted on an interactive, lightweight map."""
        x = df['lat'][i]
        y = df['lng'][i]
        marker = folium.CircleMarker(location=[x, y])
        marker.add_to(map)

The following executes mapping the coordinates:¶

In [6]:
folmap = folium.Map(location=[0, 0], zoom_start=3, tiles="CartoDB positron")
plotPoints(df, folmap)
show(folmap)
Out[6]:

After attempting to plot the points unmodified, it became clear they were "shrunk" by an unknown value, as seen above.¶

I then created the function below to expand all the coordinates:¶

In [7]:
def expandCoords(df, multiplier):
    # multiplies all coordinates in dataframe by a given multiplier.
    for x in range(len(df)):
        df['lat'][x] = (df['lat'][x] * multiplier)
        df['lng'][x] = (df['lng'][x] * multiplier)

After doing numerous tests which won't be shown in this notebook, it became clear the mulitplier was in relation to radians, so I concluded it to be 180/pi. ¶

In [8]:
mult = 180/math.pi

expandCoords(df, mult)
print(df.head(n=5))

Replotting the points after expansion, the following is produced:¶

In [9]:
newfolmap = folium.Map(location=[42.366083, -71.082194], zoom_start=2, tiles="CartoDB positron")
plotPoints(df, newfolmap)
show(newfolmap)
